{"id":"boil","term":"Boil","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>(rendered “botch” in <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 28:27\">Deut. 28:27</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 28:35\">35</a>), an aggravated ulcer, as in the case of Hezekiah (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Kings 20:7\">2 Kings 20:7</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 38:21\">Isa. 38:21</a>) or of the Egyptians (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Exodus 9:9\">Ex. 9:9</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Exodus 9:10\">10</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Exodus 9:11\">11</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 28:27\">Deut. 28:27</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 28:35\">35</a>). It designates the disease of Job (2:7), which was probably the black leprosy.</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Deuteronomy 28:27","Deuteronomy 28:35","2 Kings 20:7","Isaiah 38:21","Exodus 9:9","Exodus 9:10","Exodus 9:11"]}